s how Dutchess County's black residents overcame such obstacles to establish independent community institutions, engage in political activism, and fashion a vibrant racial consciousness in antebellum New York. By drawing attention to the African American experience in the rural Mid-Hudson Valley, this book provides new perspectives on slavery and emancipation in New York, black community formation, and the nature of black identity in the Early Republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identityzHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aAfrican AmericanszHudson River Valley (N.Y and N.J.)xHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xRace identity. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zDutchess CountyxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew YorkzDutchess CountyxHistory. 0aAntislavery movementszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aDutchess CountyxHistory. 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipationzNew York (State) 0aSlaveryzNew York (State)zDutchess CountyxHistory. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzNew York (State). 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846458940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438464589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438464589/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles